Sophonisba is just as full of borrowings from Mon- taigne as The Dutch Courtezan and The Fawn are3 but I do not think I ought to occupy more space than is necessary to prove that statement in outline. The philosophy of Act II. sc. i. from l. 1 to l. 86 is de- rived in great part from the Essays, Book III. chap. i.; and Marston was attracted to this chapter by its story of Tiberius, who refused to countenance the assassin- ation by poison of his arch-enemy Ariminius.
